{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616414"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:03:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:03:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16387"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16387"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9078"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116513"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9078"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16387"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98506"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7557"},{"type":"tags","id":"10367"},{"type":"tags","id":"10416"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21574"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21579"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116513"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe visual pathway consists of several structures that relay information from the retina to the primary visual cortex. Each structure has a specific role in processing and transmitting visual signals.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the white matter tract that carries visual information from the lateral geniculate nucleus to the primary visual cortex?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Optic nerve","Internal capsule","Optic radiations","Optic tract","Corona radiata"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic radiations\u003C/strong\u003E are white matter tracts that carry visual information from the lateral geniculate nucleus of the thalamus to the primary visual cortex in the occipital lobe. They course through the temporal lobe (forming Meyer\u0027s loop) and parietal lobe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E carries visual information from the retina to the optic chiasm, representing an earlier component of the visual pathway. The \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal capsule\u003C/strong\u003E contains multiple white matter tracts but is not specifically responsible for visual information transmission. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic tract\u003C/strong\u003E connects the optic chiasm to the lateral geniculate nucleus, occurring before the optic radiations in the visual pathway. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorona radiata\u003C/strong\u003E contains projection fibres from multiple systems but is not specifically a visual pathway structure. Understanding the course of the optic radiations is clinically important as lesions can cause specific homonymous visual field defects depending on their location.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The optic radiations are white matter tracts that carry visual information from the lateral geniculate nucleus to the primary visual cortex.","The optic radiations course through the temporal lobe (Meyer\u0027s loop) and parietal lobe to reach the occipital cortex.","The optic radiations are the final part of the visual pathway before information reaches the primary visual cortex."],"references":["Peltier J, Travers N, Destrieux C, Velut S. Optic radiations: a microsurgical anatomical study. J Neurosurg. 2006 Aug;105(2):294-300. doi: 10.3171/jns.2006.105.2.294. PMID: 17219837.","Rodrigues EM, Isolan GR, Becker LG, Dini LI, Vaz MAS, Frigeri TM. Anatomy of the optic radiations from the white matter fiber dissection perspective: A literature review applied to practical anatomical dissection. Surg Neurol Int. 2022 Jul 22;13:309. doi: 10.25259/SNI_1157_2021. PMID: 35928310; PMCID: PMC9345124.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98506"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16387"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98506"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T16:03:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T16:05:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9078"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116513"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving 